    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cable Channel's Advertising Reveals a Poor Attitude</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Fishman letter on June 25 article on ads for Invisible Man television show in restaurant restrooms notes Sci-Fi Channel's senior marketing vice president Josh Greenberg was primary architect of campaign (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re '' 'Invisible Man' Ads, in Restrooms, Become Hard to Find Themselves'' (June 25): I knew there was something wrong with the thinking at the Sci-Fi Channel when they canceled the beloved show ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' last year, showing no concern for the protests of the loyal audience.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re '' 'Invisible Man' Ads, in Restrooms, Become Hard to Find Themselves'' (June 25): I knew there was something wrong with the thinking at the Sci-Fi Channel when they canceled the beloved show ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' last year, showing no concern for the protests of the loyal audience.</p>
        <p>Now, after reading about their ''Invisible Man'' talking posters campaign, I know what the problem is: executives like Josh Greenberg, Sci-Fi Channel's senior vice president of marketing, who admits that ''Advertising these days is incredibly invasive,'' yet was a primary architect of the campaign.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL FISHMAN  Upper West Side</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
